{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522803"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:48:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:48:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13848"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13848"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.02,0.04,0.83,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6465"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111251"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6465"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13848"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93383"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1170"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2118"},{"type":"tags","id":"2401"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12789"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41710"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42948"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43445"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111251","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111251"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of fever, chills, and productive cough. She has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus. Her medications include metformin and lisinopril. She does not smoke and works as a retired teacher. On examination, she appears unwell with a pulse rate of 115/min, blood pressure 85/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 38.9\u00b0C. Her chest examination reveals crackles in the right lower zone. She has passed minimal urine in the last six hours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count: 18 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EC-reactive protein: 180 mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESerum creatinine: 218 \u03bcmol/L (45-90)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBlood urea nitrogen: 18 mmol/L (2.5-6.4)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ELactate: 3.5 mmol/L (0.5-1.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bedside bladder scan","Administer intravenous albumin","Commence haemodialysis","Administer intravenous fluid bolus","Insert urinary catheter"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with sepsis, likely due to pneumonia, complicated by pre-renal acute kidney injury (AKI). The most appropriate first step in management is to administer an \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous fluid bolus\u003C/strong\u003E. Early and aggressive fluid resuscitation is crucial in sepsis management, especially when there are signs of organ hypoperfusion such as oliguria and elevated lactate. Fluid resuscitation aims to improve tissue perfusion, including renal perfusion, which can help reverse pre-renal AKI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBedside bladder scan\u003C/strong\u003E would be useful to assess for urinary retention as a cause of oliguria, but in the context of sepsis with hypotension and elevated lactate, the oliguria is most likely due to pre-renal causes from hypoperfusion. While bladder scanning may be performed as part of the assessment, it should not delay urgent fluid resuscitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister intravenous albumin\u003C/strong\u003E is not the preferred initial fluid for resuscitation in sepsis. Current guidelines recommend crystalloids (such as normal saline or balanced crystalloids) as first-line fluids for sepsis resuscitation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence haemodialysis\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated at this stage. The patient\u0027s renal dysfunction is likely pre-renal and potentially reversible with appropriate fluid resuscitation and treatment of the underlying sepsis. Dialysis would only be considered if there were life-threatening complications of AKI such as refractory acidosis, refractory hyperkalaemia, refractory fluid overload or symptomatic uraemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Einsert urinary catheter\u003C/strong\u003E may be helpful for accurate urine output monitoring, it is not the most urgent intervention. Addressing the underlying sepsis and hypoperfusion with fluid resuscitation takes priority over catheterisation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Early fluid resuscitation is crucial in managing sepsis-induced pre-renal acute kidney injury.","Crystalloids are preferred over colloids for initial fluid resuscitation in sepsis.","Acute indications for dialysis include refractory acidosis, refractory electrolyte disturbances (i.e. hyperkalaemia), intoxicants, refractory fluid overload, and symptomatic uraemia - this can be remembered by the mnemonic AEIOU."],"references":["Zarbock A, Koyner JL, Gomez H, Pickkers P, Forni L, Nadim MK, et al. Sepsis-associated acute kidney injury - treatment standard. Nephrology Dialysis Transplantation. 2023;39(1). Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37401137/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93383"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13848"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93383"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-11T20:21:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-11T20:22:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6465"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111251"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{